        feature_groups: [
            { group: 'Workflow Orchestration', items: ['Native Generative AI steps (Summarize, Extract, Translate)', 'Human-in-the-Loop approval nodes (Slack/Email gating)', 'Role-based Task assignments embedded in automations', 'Robust error-handling and "Pause/Resume" capabilities'] },
            { group: 'Integration Ecosystem', items: ['Deep bi-directional integrations with modern SaaS (Linear, Notion, Salesforce, Slack, Hubspot)', 'Multi-step action sequencing', 'Visual flowchart builder designed for non-developers', 'Team collaboration dashboarding'] }
        ],
        best_for: ['Revenue Operations (RevOps) and Sales Enablement teams', 'Customer Success Managers coordinating delicate client handoffs', 'Startup Founders needing scalable processes with extreme quality control', 'Operations teams exhausted by fragile, chaotic "Zapier spaghetti"'],
        pros: ['The "Human-in-the-Loop" architecture fundamentally solves the terrifying anxiety of pure automation, allowing a company to scale operations infinitely while guaranteeing a human catches catastrophic edge cases', 'The native integration of AI nodes (using LLMs to actively massage, read, and structure messy data mid-flight) replaces the need to write complex, fragile "Regex" or formatting code blocks', 'The user interface is exceptionally clean, collaborative, and explicitly designed for operations managers, rather than feeling like a terrifying, technical backend IDE only a DevOps engineer can understand', 'The ability to assign sequential manual tasks to humans alongside API calls creates a true "Company Playbook," rather than just a silent background script'],
        cons: ['It is a newer player in the market; it does not possess the absolutely massive, 5,000+ app integration library of an ancient titan like Zapier, requiring workarounds or Webhooks for extremely obscure, legacy software', 'While vastly easier to use for "Playbooks," elite data engineers building highly concurrent, massively parallel, terabyte-scale data pipelines will find the platform fundamentally lacking the required technical complexity', 'Relying heavily on "Human Approvals" can unintentionally defeat the purpose of automation if a critical process frequently stalls because a specific manager is on vacation and cannot click the required Slack button', 'The cost structure is deeply tied to team collaboration and action execution, meaning massive scale requires upgrading swiftly to enterprise tiers'],
        pricing_overview: '<p>Relay operates on a team-centric SaaS tiered model. The base tiers are highly collaborative, designed to undercut the massive prices of enterprise tools, often focusing pricing limits on the number of "Active Workflows" or the volume of AI tasks processed. Premium tiers unlock unlimited users, advanced granular role permissions, and dedicated support for mission-critical operations.</p>',
        comparison_summary: '<p>Relay competes directly in the brutal orchestration arena against Make (formerly Integromat) and Zapier. Zapier represents the absolute standard for "Simple App A talks to App B." Make represents the ultimate, highly complex sandbox for elite developers to build massive visual API webs. Relay differentiates itself as the *Operations Blueprint*. It recognizes that in real businesses, APIs fail and nuanced decisions must be made. By actively building "Humans" and "AI Text Processing" directly into the automation chain as explicit features, it provides a profoundly safer, more resilient way to automate a company.</p>'
